<div class="hrecipe"><span class="published"><span class="value-title" title="2011-08-01"></span></span><a href="http://www.sharonblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/maple-bacon-buttermilk-waffles.jpg"><img class="photo aligncenter size-full wp-image-3907" title="maple bacon buttermilk waffles" src="http://www.sharonblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/maple-bacon-buttermilk-waffles.jpg" alt="" width="650" height="485" /></a><a href="http://www.sharonblog.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/maple-bacon-buttermilk-waffles.jpg"><br />
</a>I recently went and acquired a waffle maker for myself, after months and months of not buying one and just putting it off. Just so I could make waffles with bacon. What can I say I know bacon is not the best for you, but I am shamefully a huge fan of it. Honestly no shame there, I love bacon. Seriously though within two hours of getting the waffle maker home, I started making these maple-bacon buttermilk waffles.</p>
<p>These went over very well with the boys and of course I loved them and they were not difficult to make at all. The only thing that has to be worked on depending on your waffle maker is how much batter to use per waffle.</p>
<p>This was an awesome recipe and if you are a fan of waffles, bacon or both I definitely suggest you try it!</p>
